	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">MalT transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>These genes are contained in divergently transcribed operons whose 70-dependent promoters are activated by MalT when bound by ATP and maltotriose ; transcription of malT is positively regulated by cyclic AMP ( cAMP ) and cAMP receptor protein ( CRP ) ( 58 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28373272" target="_blank">28373272</a>]<br></li>
<li>Besides acting as an import system for maltose/malto-dextrins , the MalFGK2 complex is involved in the regulation of genes belonging to the maltose regulon by interaction of the MalK subunits with the positive transcriptional-regulator , MalT [ 15,31 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12225853" target="_blank">12225853</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of the operon is activated by the MalT activator protein in the presence maltose or maltodextrins ( reviewed in Schwartz , 1987 ; Boos and Shuman , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17608792" target="_blank">17608792</a>]<br></li>
<li>The malEFG operon is dependent on both the MalT regulatory protein and the cAMP/CAP complex , and is generally induced by the presence of its substrate or by free internal glucose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18048932" target="_blank">18048932</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">MalT evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>Four transcriptional regulators -- MalT ( ) , NanR ( ) , TorR ( ) , and a GntR family regulator ( ) -- as well as a transcription associated protein ( ) and an RNA polymerase associated protein ( RapA ; ) , were significantly up-regulated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26190504" target="_blank">26190504</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_RP" for="_4"><font size="5px">Processes regulated by MalT</font></label>
				<input id="_4" type="checkbox">
				<div class="RP"><br><ul><li>Besides acting as an import system for maltose/malto-dextrins , the MalFGK2 complex is involved in the regulation of genes belonging to the maltose regulon by interaction of the MalK subunits with the positive transcriptional regulator , MalT [ 15,31 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12225853" target="_blank">12225853</a>]<br></li>
<li>In E. coli , a positive role of H-NS has been described for MalT , lamB , and malE ( 19 ) , and a proteomic analysis has also revealed that H-NS has the ability to act as a positive regulator ( 25 , 36 , 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18156266" target="_blank">18156266</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by MalT</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>These genes are contained in divergently transcribed operons whose 70-dependent promoters are activated by MalT when bound by ATP and maltotriose ; transcription of malT is positively regulated by cyclic AMP ( cAMP ) and cAMP receptor protein ( CRP ) ( 58 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28373272" target="_blank">28373272</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of genes under the control of MalT was , however , signiﬁcantly reduced in the csrA mutant , approximately threeto 10-fold below the levels of the wild type ( Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12791144" target="_blank">12791144</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other MalT-activated genes require the CAP protein for expression , but the pulA and malX genes do not , possibly because of the high local concentration of the MalT regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7665482" target="_blank">7665482</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ORF of malS encodes a periplasmic α-amylase and is regulated by MalT , the activator of the maltose system in E. coli [ 35,36 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26059618" target="_blank">26059618</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of the operon is activated by the MalT activator protein in the presence maltose or maltodextrins ( reviewed in Schwartz , 1987 ; Boos and Shuman , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17608792" target="_blank">17608792</a>]<br></li>
<li>The malEFG operon is dependent on both the MalT regulatory protein and the cAMP/CAP complex , and is generally induced by the presence of its substrate or by free internal glucose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18048932" target="_blank">18048932</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul></div><br>
